The undeniably majestic island of St Michael's Mount in Mounts bay is a prominent feature across the bay and is dominantly visible for miles. St Michael's Mount is otherwise known as 'Karrek Loos yn Koos' translated as 'Hoar Rock in Woodland' believed to be due to its setting within a historic woodland prior to Mounts bay flooding some 4000 years ago. The island is one of only two tidal islands in Cornwall, the other being Asparagus island at Kynance, also within Mounts Bay.

‚ñ™Ô∏èChurch Cove, Gunwalloe, The Lizard, Cornwall

A friend of mine who was instrumental in helping the start of The Walking Drone lives close to this spectacular location and his Son also got married here. Imagine walking out of your wedding service into surroundings like this?

Gunwalloe and the Church of St Winaloe sit between two beaches and this incredible landmark dates back to the 13th century. Imagine how many weddings have taken place here? Lucky people!

As usual if you like this picture please share it. We have a beautiful county and why not show it off everyone we can? We appreciate all the shares too and love spreading the Cornish word! Meur ras beauties.

‚ñ™Ô∏èPendeen Lighthouse, Portheras Cove , Cornwall

In the exposed, rugged and far west of Cornwall you'll find some of the most spectacular and sheer cliff faces. This area is dominated by vertical and castellated granite cams making it popular for climbers and hikers alike. Pendeen Lighthouse is a Trinity House built lighthouse and while automated now is still accessible by visitors and you can even rent the cottages as a holiday retreat. You can pretend to be a lighthouse keeper to your hearts content! üòÅ 
A relatively rare sight along this coastline are sandy and large beaches but the ones that you do find are usually pristine, quiet and difficult to get to. This isn't an exception but with clear perfect waters and a Robinson Crusoe feel it is certainly worth the hike.

‚ñ™Ô∏èTrebarwith Strand, Cornwall

Before the crowds descended on Cornwall, Trebarwith Strand looked a little less busy but no less tropical and sunny. One of North Cornwalls little/big Gems and at low tide a substantial 800m long beach make this the largest beach in the area by a long shot (until you get down to the Camel Estuary of course)

This beautiful little village and its staggering coastline, cliffs, caves and beach can only be accessed by a narrow and limited parking roadway so be advised that arriving early is essential to claim your turf on the beach. 
The local geology down here is a variety of granite and slate with the famous Delabole slate quarry to the South East of Trebarwith. This construction makes for some impressive formations and incredible caves along the length of the beach. Lots of rock pools and within walking distance of Tintagel this is a welcome stop on any Cornish adventure.

Please bare in mind that with most places in Cornwall this summer we have become victim to a great deal of litter being left on our beaches. Could we please remind people to ensure you always take away what you brought and keep Cornwall looking as good as it can. üòÅüôåü§òThank you!

As usual if this picture takes your fancy why not show it off? We have a beautiful county and why not show everyone 'what you got' We appreciate all the shares too and love spreading the Cornish word! Meur ras beauties.

‚ñ™Ô∏èTrebah Beach, Helford River, Cornwall

Looking over the beach at the beautiful Trebah Garden on the Helford River and out beyond Mawnan. In the very distance you can even see St Mawes and St Anthony's lighthouse in this shot.

Its been idilic recently and it was inevitable really (especially during the school holidays) that it would change. I for one am glad to see a bit of rain because the land will have some opportunity to become lush again. If we are to believe the forecast the rain will be short lived and we'll be out in the sun again in no time.

If you haven't already the Helford is a stunning place to explore, especially by boat! Have you been here before?
